<body>
    <%- include('partials/header') %>

    <main>
    <h1>Machine Learning Models</h1>

    <section>
        <h2>1. Logistic Regression</h2>
        <p>
            Logistic Regression is used to estimate the probability that a given month
            is in recession based on past economic and financial indicators.
        </p>

        <h3>1.1 Overview</h3>
        <p>
            The model uses lagged and rolling features (3–12 months) to capture early
            warning signals before recessions occur.
        </p>

        <h3>1.2 Model Setup</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Model A:</b> Macro (Unemployment, Inflation, Interest)</li>
            <li><b>Model B:</b> Financial (S&P 500, VIX, Gold)</li>
            <li><b>Model C:</b> All features combined</li>
            <li><b>Model D:</b> Macro + S&P 500</li>
        </ul>

        <p style="font-size: 0.95em; color: #555; margin-top: 10px;">
            <b>Side Note:</b> The models are separated for two main reasons. First, to compare the predictive power of 
            macroeconomic indicators versus financial market indicators. Second, because the datasets have different 
            time coverage, as financial variables such as VIX and gold are only available from 1990 onward.
            <br><br>
            Additionally, oil prices were excluded because they introduced noise and 
            did not improve predictive performance. 
            <br><br>
            In Model D, VIX and gold were removed to extend the dataset further back in time, 
            allowing the model to cover a longer historical period.
        </p>

        <h3>1.3 Model Comparison</h3>
        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>Model</th>
                <th>Precision</th>
                <th>Recall</th>
                <th>F1</th>
                <th>ROC-AUC</th>
                <th>Summary</th>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>A (Macro)</td>
                <td>0.88</td>
                <td>0.70</td>
                <td>0.78</td>
                <td>0.984</td>
                <td>Strong balance, stable early-warning signal</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>B (Financial)</td>
                <td>0.13</td>
                <td>1.00</td>
                <td>0.24</td>
                <td>0.949</td>
                <td>Captures all recessions but produces false alarms</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>C (Combined)</td>
                <td>0.06</td>
                <td>1.00</td>
                <td>0.12</td>
                <td>0.949</td>
                <td>High sensitivity, but very noisy predictions</td>
            </tr>

            <tr>
                <td>D (Macro + SP500)</td>
                <td>0.74</td>
                <td>0.85</td>
                <td>0.79</td>
                <td>0.979</td>
                <td>Best trade-off between stability and early detection</td>
            </tr>
        </table>

        <h4>How to Read the Metrics</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Precision:</b> Of all recession warnings, what percentage were correct</li>
            <li><b>Recall:</b> Of all actual recessions, what percentage of actual recessions did the model catch</li>
            <li><b>F1 Score:</b> Balance between catching recessions and avoiding false alarms</li>
            <li><b>ROC-AUC:</b> Ability to separate recession vs normal periods (1 = perfect, 0.5 = random guessing)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>1.4 Confusion Matrix</h3>
        <figure>
            <img src="images\ML\LR-confusion-matrix.png" alt="Confusion Matrix">
            <figcaption>Figure 1. Logistic Regression confusion matrix.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>1.5 Recession Probability</h3>
        <p>
            Each point shows the model’s estimated probability of a recession for that month, using only information available up to that time.
            Red shaded areas represent actual recession periods.
        </p>

        <p>
            A good early-warning model should show rising probability before recessions begin, falling probability after they end, and minimal spikes outside recession periods to avoid false alarms.
        </p>

        <p>
            Logistic Regression produces smooth and sustained probability curves that rise gradually
            before recessions and remain elevated during recession periods. The signals are generally
            well-timed and confident, with particularly strong performance during the 2008 Great Recession
            and the COVID-19 downturn in Models A and D.
        </p>

        <p>
            However, the model can remain at high probability even after a recession has ended.
            This is most noticeable in Model C, where the model continues to flag the 2021–2024 period
            as recessionary, indicating slower adjustment to post-recession recovery.
        </p>

        <figure>
            <img src="\images\ML\LR-recession-probability.png" alt="Recession Probability">
            <figcaption>Figure 2. Logistic Regression predicted probability over time.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3>1.6 Key Insight</h3>
        <p>
            Macro indicators provide the most reliable early warning signals,
            while financial indicators react faster but generate more false alarms.
        </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Future section -->
    <section>
    <h2>2. Random Forest</h2>

    <p>
        Random Forest is a tree-based ensemble model that captures non-linear relationships
        between economic indicators. Unlike Logistic Regression, it can model more complex
        interactions without assuming a linear relationship between variables.
    </p>

    <h3>2.1 Overview</h3>
    <p>
        The same feature setup is used as in Logistic Regression, including lagged and rolling
        features (3–12 months). This allows a direct comparison between linear and non-linear models.
    </p>

    <h3>2.2 Model Setup</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Model A:</b> Macro (Unemployment, Inflation, Interest)</li>
        <li><b>Model B:</b> Financial (S&amp;P 500, VIX, Gold)</li>
        <li><b>Model C:</b> All features combined</li>
        <li><b>Model D:</b> Macro + S&amp;P 500</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.3 Model Comparison</h3>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Model</th>
            <th>Precision</th>
            <th>Recall</th>
            <th>F1</th>
            <th>ROC-AUC</th>
            <th>Summary</th>
        </tr>

        <tr>
            <td>A (Macro)</td>
            <td>1.00</td>
            <td>0.05</td>
            <td>0.10</td>
            <td>0.938</td>
            <td>Very conservative, misses most recessions</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
            <td>B (Financial)</td>
            <td>0.15</td>
            <td>1.00</td>
            <td>0.27</td>
            <td>0.907</td>
            <td>Detects all recessions but produces many false alarms</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
            <td>C (Combined)</td>
            <td>1.00</td>
            <td>1.00</td>
            <td>1.00</td>
            <td>1.000</td>
            <td>Perfect fit, likely overfitting due to limited recession samples</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
            <td>D (Macro + SP500)</td>
            <td>1.00</td>
            <td>0.20</td>
            <td>0.33</td>
            <td>0.976</td>
            <td>Improves detection slightly, but still misses many recessions</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h4>How to Read the Metrics</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Precision:</b> Of all recession warnings, what percentage were correct</li>
        <li><b>Recall:</b> Of all actual recessions, what percentage the model successfully detected</li>
        <li><b>F1 Score:</b> Balance between detection and false alarms</li>
        <li><b>ROC-AUC:</b> Overall ability to distinguish recession vs normal periods</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.4 Confusion Matrix</h3>
    <p>
        The Random Forest model performs well in identifying non-recession periods,
        but struggles to consistently detect recessions.
    </p>

    <p>
        Some models are too conservative (missing recessions), while others capture all
        recessions but generate false alarms. The combined model shows perfect results,
        likely due to overfitting.
    </p>

    <figure>
        <img src="images/ML/RF-confusion-matrix.png" alt="Random Forest Confusion Matrix">
        <figcaption>Figure 3. Random Forest confusion matrix.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>2.5 Recession Probability</h3>
    <p>
        The Random Forest model estimates recession probabilities over time, but the signals
        are less stable compared to Logistic Regression.
    </p>

    <p>
        Probabilities tend to either stay too low (delayed detection) or spike sharply
        (false alarms), making early warning less consistent.
    </p>

    <figure>
        <img src="images/ML/RF-recession-probability.png" alt="Random Forest Recession Probability">
        <figcaption>Figure 4. Random Forest predicted probability over time.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>2.6 Key Insight</h3>
    <p>
        Random Forest captures complex patterns in the data but struggles with limited recession samples.
        While it achieves very high accuracy in some cases, it often either misses recessions entirely
        (low recall) or overfits when too many features are included.
    </p>

    <p>
        Compared to Logistic Regression, Random Forest does not consistently improve early-warning performance.
        This suggests that simpler, more interpretable models may be more reliable for recession prediction
        when data is limited.
    </p>
</section>

</main>

